Jessica Chamberlain Gafford is with Amber Geter Thorne and 4 others.
May 13 at 10:40 AM ¬∑

Sappy post warning: This morning I did something so fun! The senior showcase is amazing. This is a silver lining in this funky time. As a Kindergarten teacher I get the pleasure of teaching little people. Most of the time when they leave me I see them a couple of times at Rollins Place. Most of them are frozen in time in my mind as "My Kinder-babies". That is until I see one in the news paper, in a play, pulling a wagon in our parade, or playing sports. Unfortunately, I usually do not see many of them ever again.
If you are a teacher, do your ‚ù§ some good and check it out. These are some of "My Kinder-babies" that are graduating. Also, something strange (miraculous) happened yesterday. I happened upon a couple of class-made books and work done by these kiddos that was saved all these yearsü•∞
*please share with any who may know these kiddos. I'd love for all of them to see this message.

Bronco Robotics Team 6489
April 14 at 8:19 PM ¬∑

One of the little known side effects of wearing surgical masks for an extended period of time is the sores that it can leave on back of our health professionals ears. Today, Bronco Robotics team members Hailey and Colin delivered 3D printed straps that can relieve their ears from the rubber straps on the important masks that they must wear to protect them while fighting this pandemic from the front lines. Please help us to thank them for constantly looking for ways to brighten this crazy world we are living in. And to all of the health care heroes, first responders, and essential workers putting their lives and their families lives in danger for the protection of others, we cannot thank you enough. #ourheroeswearscrubs #nothanksareenough #stayhome #staysafe #stayhealthy

Celebrating excellence! Kristy Gilpin has been named the March Teacher of the Month for Dream Teachers. Kristy is the Library Media Specialist at Rollins Place Elementary in Zachary, LA. She is a National Board Certified teacher, Nat Geo Certified Educator, Seesaw Ambassador, and Fellow with the Louisiana A+ Schools network. All of these distinctions give her an opportunity to work with teachers and pursue her passions for using technology in education, integrating the arts in curriculum and developing students who are curious, responsible, and empowered. You can learn more about Kristy and her impact on her students, fellow teachers, and community at www.dreamteachers.org!

Today in P.E., our Mustangs talked about cost associated with buying things. Students selected items to build a Mardi Gras "float".

To purchase the item, students would ‚Äúpay‚Äù the associated cost with specific exercises. They learned that things that are rare in our environment, or have a higher demand, cost more.

What a sweet ending to our week! This afternoon, both our boys and girls were treated to visits from special guests.

Our girls gathered, in their unicorn shirts and accessories, to hear the story of The Nuff. This special book was written by Zachary resident, the late Veronica Waldrop, as a way to encourage her young daughters and girls everywhere. Dear friends of Veronica‚Äôs shared a few words about her life and then read the story to our little Wranglers. Thanks to a generous donation from a community member, every girl at RPE received a copy of the picture book.

Our boys were treated to a visit from Zach Von Rosenburg, a Zachary native, punter for the LSU National Championship team, and former MLB player for the Pittsburgh Pirates. He spoke with our boys about setting goals and working hard to make their dreams happen!

#WeAreZachary #TheNuff #GeauxTigers

These students from Mrs. Messina's class were able to cash in "money" earned in Messina Marketplace to eat lunch with Ms. Thomas & Mrs. Noel today!

Check out how it works:
Income - Students get paid every other week for performing their classroom jobs and for showing positive behavior around school.

Rent & Taxes - Students must pay for their desks and seats every week and can get taxed for negative behavior around school.

Market Days - Every Friday, students can visit Messina Marketplace and spend their money on a variety of different things. They vary from candy ($50) to lunch with Ms. Thomas and Mrs. Noel ($1,000)!

Way to go, Mustangs! Keep up the good work!

Zachary Elementary School
February 3 at 5:39 PM ¬∑

Happy Monday! Here are some of our Mustangs having fun and learning with cup stacking.

Did you know that sport stacking (cup stacking) promotes not just physical fitness, but also academic learning? Students that sport stack on a regular basis have shown increases in test scores and levels of concentration. This is achieved by students using both their right and left sides of the brain. When students sport stack, they are crossing the "mid-line" of their bodies and developing new connections in their brains. Go, Mustangs!
